# Cursor Rules for IntelOdds Project

## Windows Development Environment
- This project runs on Windows 11 - use Windows-compatible commands
- Use `dir` instead of `ls` for directory listing
- Use `cd` for directory navigation
- Use `;` to separate commands instead of `&&` for command chaining
- Use PowerShell commands: `Get-ChildItem`, `Set-Location`, etc.
- Use Windows path separators: `\` instead of `/`
- Use `copy` and `move` instead of `cp` and `mv`
- Use `del` or `Remove-Item` instead of `rm`

## JavaScript/HTML/CSS Conventions
- Use camelCase for variables and functions
- Use PascalCase for classes and components
- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants
- Use 2 spaces for indentation
- Use single quotes for strings when possible
- Use semicolons at the end of statements
- Use meaningful variable and function names

## Project-Specific Rules
- Follow the existing code structure and patterns in the IntelOdds project
- Maintain the existing UI/UX patterns
- Preserve the existing data visualization patterns
- Keep the existing event handling patterns
- Maintain the existing file organization structure

## File Organization
- Keep related functionality together in appropriate directories
- Use descriptive file and folder names
- Add comments for complex logic
- Maintain the existing public_html structure

## Error Handling
- Always include try-catch blocks for error-prone operations
- Log errors to console with descriptive messages
- Provide user-friendly error messages when appropriate
- Handle network errors gracefully

## UI/UX Guidelines
- Maintain responsive design principles
- Ensure accessibility standards are met
- Use consistent styling patterns
- Follow modern web development best practices 